# 5 Runtime Event Kernel
## 5.1 Design Rationale
Traditional agent architectures use direct function calls between modules, introducing:
- Unpredictable dependency chains hard to audit
- No global replay capability for failure recovery
- Unregulated cross-subsystem state leakage
- Difficult parallel scheduling & resource isolation

Runtime Event Kernel solves these via a standardized asynchronous event bus, enforcing message-passing as the only inter-subsystem communication protocol.

## 5.2 Full Kernel Structure
```mermaid
flowchart LR
    SUB[All OS Subsystems / Perception / Governor] --> INBOX[Event Inbox Router]
    INBOX --> AUDIT[Event Audit Engine]
    AUDIT --> STORE[Persistent Runtime Event Store]
    STORE --> REPLAY[Offline Replay Controller]
    AUDIT --> BUS[Unified Event Dispatch Bus]
    BUS --> SUB
```
## 5.3 Core Capabilities
1. Audit: Every event metadata, payload, timestamp and sender identity logged persistently
2. Replay: Entire runtime execution trace can be replayed for debugging, fine-tuning cognitive logic
3. Isolation: Subsystems only consume subscribed event types; no direct memory sharing
4. Serialization: Uniform event schema compatible with local disk storage

Status: 🟡 In Progress

